i1 Ã Ã Ã il, system k is maximally entangled with the remaining systems. Thus, two states jÃ‰i, jÃˆi with i1ÃÃÃil;k Â¼ i1ÃÃÃil  1 and i1ÃÃÃil;k Ã i1ÃÃÃil  1 can neither be LU equivalent nor possess the same entanglement. Hence, the method presented above suggests that in order to characterize the nonlocal properties of multipartite states, one should ï¬rst identify the class (as described above) to which the state belongs to and then determine within this class the entanglement of the state. It might well be that the different classes lead to different applications. For instance, the states used for error correction and oneway quantum computing have the property that all single qubit reduced states are completely mixed.
In order to illustrate the power of this method we consider ï¬rst the simplest examples of two and three-qubit states. The standard form of a two-qubit state is jÃ‰i Â¼ 1j00i Ã¾ 2j11i. Thus, the method above tells us that if 1 Ã 2, i.e., i Ã 1, then jÃ‰i â€™LU jÃˆi iff the Schmidt coefï¬cients i are the same. For 1 Â¼ 2 it is straightforward to show that the unitaries Ui, which are obtained using the method above for the states jÃˆÃ¾i  j00i Ã¾ j11i and some LU-equivalent state V1V2jÃˆÃ¾i are U1 Â¼ V1W and U2 Â¼ V2WÃƒ for any unitary W. The reason why the unitaries Ui are not completely determined by Vi is due to the symmetry of jÃˆÃ¾i. For three qubits the method is almost equally simple. First, we transform both states into their trace decomposition. If none of the reduced states is completely mixed, we simply compare their standard forms (Theorem 1). If there exists some i such that i Ã 1, we know that Ui Â¼ ZÃ°iÃ. We measure system i in the computational basis and are left with two two-qubit states [see Eq. (2)]. For the remaining case, where i Â¼ 1 8 i it can be easily shown that jÃ‰i is LU equivalent to the GHZ state, jÃ‰0i Â¼ j000i Ã¾ j111i [17]. Even without using this fact also in this case the right unitaries can be directly computed using the presented method (for, details see [17]).
The LU-equivalence classes of up to 5-qubit states are investigated in [17]. We will show there, for instance, that for 4-qubit states with ij Â¼ 1 for some i, j (which is the hardest class of states using the method presented above), the LU-equivalence class is determined by only three parameters. Thus, the entanglement of those states is completely determined by the fact that system ij is maximally entangled to the other two qubits and those three parameters, to which also an operational meaning will be given [17]. This example shows already that the method presented here does not only give necessary and sufï¬cient conditions for the LU equivalence of arbitrary multipartite states, but also leads to a new insight into their entanglement properties. Moreover, the results presented here lead also to a criterion of LU equivalence for certain mixed and also d-level states [17] and to conditions for the existence of more general operations transforming one state into the other, namely local operations and classical communica-

tion (LOCC). This is due to the fact that two multipartite states, having the same marginal one-party entropies, are either LU equivalent, or LOCC incomparable [19].
